  "answer": "c) This child has a classical history for esophageal atresia and has a very high (90% or more) probability of a distal tracheoesophageal fistula. The simplest way to establish the diagnosis is to attempt to pass a catheter through the mouth or nose into the stomach. If the tube encounters obstruction, a plain radiograph should document the atresia. Patients with esophageal atresia and tracheoesophageal fistula frequently have associated anomalies. This incidence is about 30% to 50% in most reports. Anomalies vary from minor skeletal deformities to uncorrectable cardiac defects. The most common associated anomalies are cardiac and gastrointestinal, especially imperforate anus (10%). Vertebral, genitourinary and limb anomalies are also seen. Importantly, approximately 5% of patients with esophageal atresia have a right-sided aortic arch. This is an important technical issue as the normal approach is via a right thoracotomy and this should be changed to a left thoracotomy in the presence of this finding. There is no association with hydrocephalus.",
