  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's: the 2% rule, 5 ways to ruin your day.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Meckel’s diverticulum, the most common congenital anomaly of the GI tract, is notorious for its varied clinical presentations. All listed options—hemorrhage, intussusception, volvulus, patent omphalomesenteric duct, and right lower quadrant peritoneal findings—are well-documented manifestations of this condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel’s diverticulum is a remnant of the omphalomesenteric (vitelline) duct, typically located on the antimesenteric border of the ileum. Its clinical diversity stems from its potential for ectopic tissue (most commonly gastric mucosa, leading to hemorrhage via ulceration), its anatomical structure (acting as a lead point for intussusception or a fibrous band causing volvulus and obstruction), or inflammation (diverticulitis, often mimicking appendicitis and causing RLQ peritoneal signs). A persistent patent duct can also present as an umbilical fistula.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options (Hemorrhage, Intussusception, Volvulus, Patent omphalomesenteric duct, Right lower quadrant peritoneal findings) are correct presentations of Meckel's diverticulum. Therefore, there are no incorrect options to address.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Presentation | Approximate Frequency (%) | Underlying Mechanism |\n| :-------------------- | :------------------------ | :------------------- |\n| Hemorrhage            | 30–35                     | Ectopic gastric mucosa causing ulceration |\n| Small Bowel Obstruction (Intussusception, Volvulus) | 30–35                     | Diverticulum as lead point or fibrous band |\n| Diverticulitis        | 20–25                     | Inflammation of the diverticulum |\n| Umbilical Fistula     | 10                        | Persistent patent omphalomesenteric duct |\n| RLQ Peritoneal Findings | Variable (often due to diverticulitis) | Localized inflammation or perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meckel's: the 2% rule, 5 ways to cause trouble.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan (Meckel's scan) can identify ectopic gastric mucosa, which is the cause of hemorrhage. Intraoperatively, a Meckel's diverticulum appears as a true diverticulum on the antimesenteric border of the ileum, typically 2 feet from the ileocecal valve.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSpecific society guidelines solely dedicated to Meckel's diverticulum are not common. Management principles are generally covered within broader pediatric surgical or general surgical textbooks and consensus statements on small bowel pathology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Patent omphalomesenteric duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Right lower quadrant peritoneal findings | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c, d, e) The most frequent congenital anomaly of the GI tract is a Meckel’s diverticulum. The incidence is ab** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 77346718-Medical-Facts-and-Mcq-s-Pediatric-Surgery-Mcq.txt**\n",
