  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neuroblastoma: a young child's abdominal mass, N-myc is bad news.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies that statements a, b, and c are true regarding neuroblastoma. These statements accurately reflect key epidemiological and prognostic factors essential for understanding this common pediatric malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma is indeed the most common abdominal malignancy of childhood, originating from neural crest cells and often presenting as an adrenal or paraspinal mass. Its peak incidence in early childhood, with 80% of diagnoses occurring before age 4, highlights the importance of early recognition. The N-myc oncogene's amplification is a critical prognostic marker; increased copy numbers are directly linked to more aggressive disease and significantly worse survival, guiding risk stratification and treatment intensity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption d (Incorrect): Trk proto-oncogene expression is *directly* related to survival probability, not inversely. Higher Trk-A expression is associated with a better prognosis and lower stage disease.\nOption e (Incorrect): Since option d is false, 'All of the above' cannot be true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | N-myc Amplification | Trk-A Expression |\n|---|---|---|\n| Prognosis | Poor (inversely related to survival) | Good (directly related to survival) |\n| Correlation with each other | Inversely correlated | Inversely correlated with N-myc amplification |\n| Clinical Significance | High-risk factor, guides therapy | Favorable prognostic factor, associated with lower stage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: N-myc amplification means bad prognosis; Trk-A expression means good prognosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNeuroblastoma typically appears as an irregular, often calcified, suprarenal or paraspinal mass on imaging. Intraoperatively, it can be a firm, lobulated tumor, sometimes encasing major vessels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (e.g., ANBL1231, ANBL1531). These guidelines use age, stage, N-myc status, and other biological factors for risk stratification and treatment assignment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Neuroblastoma is the most common abdominal malignancy of childhood | ✅ Correct |\n| b | Approximately 80% of neuroblastoma patients are diagnosed prior to age 4 ye | ✅ Correct |\n| c | N-myc oncogene copy number in neuroblastoma tissue is inversely related to  | ✅ Correct |\n| d | Trk proto-oncogene expression in neuroblastoma tissue is inversely related  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c) Neuroblastoma is the most common extracranial solid tumor and the most common abdominal malignancy o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 77346718-Medical-Facts-and-Mcq-s-Pediatric-Surgery-Mcq.txt**\n",
