  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 RMS: From 20% to 50% survival, thanks to smart multimodal teamwork.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct statements accurately reflect the current multimodal treatment paradigm for rhabdomyosarcoma, which combines tailored surgical resection with systemic chemotherapy, and the significant improvement in overall survival rates achieved through these strategies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRhabdomyosarcoma management has undergone a profound evolution from primarily surgical resection, which historically yielded only 20% survival. The integration of chemotherapy and radiation therapy has transformed outcomes, boosting overall survival to approximately 50%. Current surgical strategies are nuanced, advocating for complete resection of small, noninvasive lesions upfront, or delayed resection after chemotherapy-induced tumor regression for larger, more formidable tumors, thereby optimizing local control while minimizing morbidity. This multimodal approach underscores the critical role of systemic therapy in managing this aggressive pediatric malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Surgical resection alone historically resulted in only 20% survival, not 80-90%, before the advent of effective chemotherapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Alveolar histology is actually associated with a poor prognosis, not a favorable one, due to its aggressive nature and common association with fusion genes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Embryonal RMS | Alveolar RMS | Pleomorphic RMS (Adult) |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- |\n| **Prevalence** | Most common subtype (60-70%) | Second most common (20-25%) | Rare in children, more common in adults |\n| **Prognosis** | Generally more favorable | Poor prognosis, aggressive | Variable, often aggressive |\n| **Genetics** | Often loss of heterozygosity at 11p15.5 | PAX3-FOXO1 or PAX7-FOXO1 fusion genes | Complex chromosomal rearrangements |\n| **Common Sites** | Head/neck (orbit), genitourinary, retroperitoneum | Extremities, trunk, perineum | Extremities, trunk |\n| **Treatment Impact**| Often responds well to chemotherapy | Requires intensive multimodal therapy | Aggressive surgical resection and systemic therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Multimodal therapy, not surgery alone, defines modern RMS survival.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), rhabdomyosarcoma typically appears as a soft tissue mass, often heterogeneous with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, and can invade adjacent structures. Intraoperatively, these tumors are often soft, friable, and poorly demarcated, making complete resection challenging without preoperative chemotherapy for larger lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Guidelines for Rhabdomyosarcoma (e.g., 2020-2023). These guidelines recommend risk-stratified, multimodal therapy including surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation based on histology, stage, and group.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical resection of the primary tumor results in cure of approximately 80 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Currently recommended therapy includes complete resection of primary tumors | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Alveolar histology is a favorable prognostic finding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Overall survival of all patients is now approximately 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, d) Surgical resection of the primary tumor was the mainstay of treatment 30 years ago for rhabdomyosarc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 77346718-Medical-Facts-and-Mcq-s-Pediatric-Surgery-Mcq.txt**\n",
