  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Shrink to resect, save a child's liver.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights a crucial aspect of modern hepatoblastoma management: the ability to convert initially unresectable tumors into resectable ones through neoadjuvant chemotherapy, significantly improving long-term survival. This reflects a paradigm shift in pediatric oncology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatoblastoma, while often presenting as a large mass, benefits immensely from preoperative (neoadjuvant) chemotherapy. This strategy aims to shrink the tumor, making it amenable to complete surgical resection, which remains the cornerstone of curative treatment. This cytoreductive approach has dramatically improved outcomes for patients who would otherwise have been deemed incurable, underscoring the importance of multidisciplinary care in pediatric liver tumors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Multicentricity is uncommon in hepatoblastoma (less than 20%) and is more characteristic of hepatocellular carcinoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): Cirrhosis in the uninvolved liver is unusual in hepatoblastoma, unlike hepatocellular carcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Jaundice is an uncommon presentation for hepatoblastoma; patients typically present with an abdominal mass and are otherwise well.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatoblastoma | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Multicentricity | Uncommon (<20%) | Common |\n| Cirrhosis | Unusual in surrounding liver | Often associated with cirrhosis |\n| Jaundice | Uncommon | Can be present, especially with advanced disease |\n| AFP | Elevated in ~90% | Elevated in many, but not all, cases |\n| Treatment | Chemotherapy + Resection | Resection, transplant, locoregional therapies |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neoadjuvant chemo makes unresectable hepatoblastomas resectable.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging typically reveals a single, pseudo-encapsulated liver mass, often large, without breaching the umbilical fissure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline mentioned in the provided text.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Multicentricity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cirrhosis in the uninvolved liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Unresectable tumors subjected to cytoreductive chemotherapy may be resected | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Jaundice | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c) Children with hepatoblastoma most commonly present with an abdominal mass or diffuse abdominal swell** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 77346718-Medical-Facts-and-Mcq-s-Pediatric-Surgery-Mcq.txt**\n",
